I’m choosing to step lightly into 2023. I don’t have a word for the new year, I didn’t make a vision board and I didn’t write down a list of intentions. And that’s ok. The past couple of years I’ve set big goals for starting off the new year strong. But, every year life seems to challenge me to take a step back and take things slow.

I always imagine the new year as the start of a new book and a new chapter. It’s exciting to jump right in, but it’s also ok to take it slow. I’m throwing away the idea I “should be doing this” or “should be doing that” out the window. This is my opportunity to chart my own path into 2023. Let’s give each other grace and encouragement for however you choose to start the new year.

My hope for 2023 is to make more room for spontaneity and enjoying the little things. When I look back on the past year it’s the small moments that brought me the most joy. A spontaneous day at the beach with my nephews, a surprise date night with Cory, evening walks in the community garden, and saying our peak and pit at the end of the day. I hope the new year brings more of this stuff.

I’m partnering with @dte_energy_official to share some tips on how to keep your gas bill low during the winter months. #ad 

First, it’s important to understand these four key factors that impact your gas bill each month. 

- Usage - The amount of gas used during a billing cycle. Working from home means we’re using a lot more energy in our home than when we had to drive into the office. 

- Weather - Extreme cold weather can make heating equipment run longer, increasing your gas use. 

- Days billed - Fewer days in the billing cycle typically results in a lower gas bill, compared to a billing cycle with more days. 

- Household changes - More people in the house often means gas appliances are used frequently. 

Here are some practical and proven ways to lower your energy use and cut down on those bills while keeping warm and cozy in winter: 

1. Install a programmable thermostat - When you are home set the thermostat as low as is comfortable. When you are asleep or out of the house, turn the thermostat down. A smart or programmable thermostat can make it easy to set the temperature in your home. Make sure the temperature is comfortable for pets! 

2. Use room sensors. These help the programmable thermostat know which rooms you’re using, and can adjust the temperature accordingly. 

3. Reduce heat loss from the fireplace - Keep the fireplace damper closed unless a fire is burning. This can help prevent warm air escaping. 

4. Dress for the weather - When you’re at home, dress in warm clothing and use a blanket.

This isn’t an easy post, and I’ve gone back and forth about sharing it on Instagram. But, what I love most about The GR Guide is this community. I tend to default in sharing the highlight reel of my life here, and don’t always do a great job including the lows. For me this platform is an equal mix of business and personal posts, so I wanted to share this with you. Also, my dad gave me permission to share.

Just a few days before Christmas my dad was diagnosed with Multiple Myeloma - a cancer of the plasma cells. Obviously this type of news is hard to hear any time of year, but the holidays were pretty difficult for us. He started treatment last month, and we are hopeful for a good outcome. But, he has a long road ahead of him and an extensive treatment plan. We’re taking things one day, one week, one month at a time. This year is going to be a roller coaster for my family, but we’re in this together. I’m so proud of how courageous and strong my dad has been through this journey. Love you dad!

From the bottom of my heart THANK YOU for well wishes, thoughts and prayers. We really appreciate it. ❤️

Here are some specific things my dad has asked we can pray for or think about: 
- That he continues to feel good. So far he’s been feeling ok after treatments.
- That the treatments work.
- The staff at the cancer center. They have been amazing, and we are so grateful for their care. 
- Consider donating to cancer research. We’ve realized how important advances in research are for cancer treatments.

Day 1 - We made it to Florence! Our first stop was San Miniato, a little town in Tuscany that’s known for their white truffles (and amazing views). It felt really good to walk around, learn about the history of this town, and grab some lunch. Next stop was our hotel to relax and enjoy happy hour together. Our hotel makes some amazing wine, and we also toured their wine cellar. A family-style Tuscan dinner was the perfect way to end the day. 

It’s been so fun to be here in Italy with family, friends, and new friends! Follow along on stories to see all of our Tuscany adventures. @wittetravelgr

Day 2 - We enjoyed a relaxing morning at the hotel before heading out for lunch at a family-run farmhouse. This farmhouse specialized in saffron and it was really interesting learning about how they harvest it. Our gnocchi with ricotta, zucchini and saffron was so good! Next stop was San Gimignano for a little tour of the city and a gelato tasting from the best gelato shop. Before dinner we took a tour of Villa Machiavelli (which was stunning). Our dinner included truffle ravioli which was a highlight of the evening. @wittetravelgr

Day 3 - We drove to a farmhouse to make cantuccini (similar to biscotti) and tagliatelle pasta. Cory learned he’s better at being a sous chef, but we all had so much fun. Our next stop was a drive up the mountains to @badia_coltibuono for a wine tasting. We really enjoyed the wine cellar tour, and seeing their collection that dates back to 1937! After wine tasting we made our way back to the hotel and had dinner together.

Day 4 - We took the train to Florence for the day. We had a walking tour around the city, and then had the afternoon to ourselves. Of course shopping, eating, and drinking were a must. Some of us also climbed the 400+ stairs to the top of the duomo. What a view 🙌. We met up in the evening for dinner before taking the train back to our hotel. @wittetravelgr

Day 5 - We started our day in Lari touring Martelli Pasta. This family-run business is amazing, and it was fun seeing the pasta being made. After Lari we made our way to Pisa. Also, Cocktails with Cory is back with an easy mocktail/cocktail using a homemade blueberry simple syrup. Cory loves making simple syrup for cocktails, and adding the fresh blueberries was a really great addition. 

Blueberry Simple Syrup:

Ingredients:
1 cup fresh blueberries 
1 cup water
1 cup granulated sugar

Instructions:
Add the ingredients to a small saucepan and bring to a bowl. Once it comes to a boil reduce the heat to a simmer for around 8-10 minutes. Remove from heat and allow the mixture to cool. Strain the mixture to remove the skins and fruit pieces. Store in a sealed container in the refrigerator. 

For the mocktail/cocktail I added some ice to a glass with the blueberry simple syrup, fresh citrus juice (lemon, lemonade, lime or even grapefruit juice), and topped it with sparkling water. I had lemon sparkling water in the house, and the mix of lemon and blueberry is obviously a great pairing. You can use your whatever sparkling water you prefer! Cory added vodka to this for a refreshing summer cocktail. Cheers!

39 weeks ✨

I can’t believe she’ll be here soon! I’m trying to soak up these final days with the bump and her kicking around. It’s truly been a beautiful journey being pregnant, but I’m looking forward to holding her in my arms.

She’s here! 

Marlowe Joy born on 11/6/23

Cory and I had a difficult time deciding on a name for her. What we did agree on was wanting a name that had a significant meaning behind it.

Marlowe means “from the hill by the lake, this name is meant to give baby a sense of comfort and home to take with them everywhere.” It made us think about summer vacations at The Homestead, and memories of my grandparent’s lake house. That feeling of comfort being at the lake is something she’s given us throughout this roller coaster of a year. 

Joy is my middle name and my mom’s middle name. Passing this name to her is really special to us. 

We are truly so thankful for this gift of new life, and God’s answers to prayers. Thank you for all your well wishes. 🩷
